text: I kinda get why people aren't feeling good about the trailer. It feels overall campy in tone with the music and the way its put together. It's really not just people being butt over it being not DC but more like how the previous movies somehow built up to this. The Thor storyline was going dark, but the trailer frames the third installment like a 100% comedy filler movie. People are going to take this like a gotg rip off or them trying to dial up the comedy in a place it really shouldn't be that high. It makes sense, especially when the only thing to go off of is the trailer. The purpose of the trailer is to give people a taste and get them in the seats from it. This time not everyone is digging it. Shit happens, but its best to understand why they just ain't feeling it this time.

text: It's got one joke in the entire trailer and it's suddenly comedy? Comedic tone I get, but calling it a comedy is exaggerating.   'Why is Thor not afraid of fighting Hulk?' 'Why is he happy to fight Hulk?'. HE'S THOR. Hulk can punch him and he's gonna be fine. If you've read at least one comic run with Thor in it, you'll know he LOVES brawling. If you haven't read one, the Thor movies would have been enough.  Personally, I'm more curious than anything about why the director decided a retro vibe to go with the movie's end-of-the-world storyline. I don't know how the movie's gonna turn out but this teaser sold me to watching the next trailers and the movie. Until I see the movie, then and only then can I tell what I think about the retro vibe about the film and how they incorporated it with a movie that tackles a serious storyline.  Like seriously, everyone needs to watch the movie first before saying how the way they tackle the movie doesn't fit the movie. Seriously. You'll enjoy watching movies more.

text: this is classic marvel, anyone who does not want to see this as an accurate comic book depiction is sorely mistaken... a cosmic being (the goldblum) gathers superheroes for a competitive yet poorly planned out fight to the death, which is not only entertaining but also kinda hilarious in a "what if" sort of way... all the while it brings them together to crush a common foe...and for those who say "but this isnt ragnarok" all i have to say to you is of course not you big dummies, comic book characters never die! even when they do! but the reference to ragnarok implies much more than thor's death, it is a change in the marvel universe (or cinematic universe in this case) which is exactly what was required of this movie just months before oh i dont know... AN INFINITY WAR?!?! ...and also im seeing people make poor backhanded comments about the obvious guardians of the galaxy similarities... WELL DUH! GotG is a successful and honed version of the marvel galaxy, and thor, believe it or not, is not from earth but ASGARD! out in the galaxy ya know?? so why would it make sense to do a galaxy story that is nothing like the previous and successful galaxy story????? stop bitching all you sorry ass fanboys and girls, and just enjoy the success of something you love... fucking christ...

text: jI ust saw it.. hands down the best Thor in the series.. and about 2X as good the previous Thor movies- note even critics that Didn't like it (you will always have haters) said it was by far the best of the franchise. Fantastic story, action, character interaction, pacing, humor, and continuity.  The Humor is there to help offset some really REALLY sad moments and events. I loved this movie because unlike the previous Thor, it makes some BIG  changes to the marvel universe and really sets things up and keeps things moving for continuity. It has a very independent bold yet fairly faithful respect to the comics.  My favorite Thor movie hands down, and most enjoyable to watch. Could easily watch it again. There are some amazing moments but none that would have you calling BS, as it is all laid out, explained and has continuity with the marvel universe and characters.. VERY well put together movie. Great performances. great everything..  10/10
